    <article id="terminology">
      <h2 class="terminology source_title">Terminology</h2>

      <h3>How does Global Forest Watch define “forest”?</h3>
      <p>Various definitions exist for the term “forest”, and GFW does not aim to provide a consensus definition. The various datasets hosted on GFW may define “forest” differently or pertain to different types of forest. Through the information on the <%= link_to "Data page", sources_path %>, we aim to be transparent about the assumptions and definitions feeding into each dataset.</p>

      <p>See the next entry for GFW’s approach to tree plantations vs natural forests.</p>

      <p>Here are key examples of how a few GFW-hosted datasets define “forest”.</p>

      <ul>
        <li>The UMD Tree Cover Loss and Gain datasets define “forest” based on <a href="http://glcf.umd.edu/data/vcf/">MODIS Vegetation Continuous Fields</a>. Forest is further defined as areas where canopy cover exceeds 25%, with vegetation over 5 m tall.</li>

        <li>FORMA Alerts apply to areas considered “forest” within the humid tropical forest biome, as defined by <a href="http://www.pnas.org/content/105/27/9439.full#ref-1">Hansen et al.(2008)</a>, based on <a href="http://wolfweb.unr.edu/~ldyer/classes/396/olsonetal.pdf">WWF’s terrestrial ecoregions</a>. This layer, a composite of forest ecoregions, is available for viewing or downloading on <a hre="https://wri-01.cartodb.com/tables/ecoregions/map">CartoDB</a>.</li>

        <li><a href="http://www.intactforests.org/ ">Intact Forest Landscapes</a> (IFL) are defined as an unbroken expanse of natural ecosystems within the zone of current forest extent, showing no signs of significant human activity and large enough that all native biodiversity, including viable populations of wide-ranging species, could be maintained. Although all IFL are within the forest zone, some may contain extensive naturally tree-less areas, including grasslands, wetlands, lakes, alpine areas, and ice. Read more <a href="http://www.intactforests.org/">here</a>.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>In our general writing, including the GFW blog, “forest” refers to a landscape with a high density of trees and value for biodiversity, carbon storage, and human use.</p>

      <h3>Do you distinguish tree plantations from natural forests?</h3>
      <p>As noted above, the various datasets hosted on GFW may define “forest” differently.</p>

      <p>Tree plantations are not distinguished from natural forests in the case of several key datasets hosted on GFW (including 2000 Forest Cover Extent, UMD tree cover loss and gain, FORMA alerts, and QUICC alerts). Tree cover loss may include cases of plantation forests being harvested, and tree cover gain may include cases where natural forests are replaced with tree plantations</p>

      <p>It is nonetheless important to <a href="http://www.sciencemag.org/content/342/6160/805.full">distinguish</a> between natural forests and tree plantations when considering conservation value, carbon storage, and value to local communities. Natural forests have higher biodiversity, store more carbon, and are more often associated with the traditional livelihoods of forest-dependent communities.</p>

      <p>Global Forest Watch users may be able to use contextual data such as concession boundaries, protected areas, and satellite imagery basemaps  to help distinguish tree plantation from natural forests. Users are also encouraged to compare data available on GFW to other datasets that may help plantations for natural forests. GFW and partners are also currently developing “plantation forests map” for the tropical regions to determine the local of plantations on a near-global scale. The map, developed through remote sensing methods, will be coming soon to the GFW site</p>

      <h3>How do you define “deforestation” and related terms (e.g. “forest loss”, “forest clearing”, “tree cover loss”, and “tree cover loss alerts”?)</h3>

      <p>The various datasets hosted on GFW have different terminology for types of forest change, and may define these terms differently. GFW does not aim to provide a consensus definition. See our <%= link_to "Data page", sources_path %> for more detail.</p>

      <p>In general writing, GFW uses “forest loss”, “forest clearing”, “forest cover loss”, “forest degradation” and similar terms to refer to the removal of a significant number of trees from a landscape. This can be the result of human use of forest landscapes or natural events. These terms are generally “gross”, not “net”, as they do not take into account regrowth of forests.</p>

      <p>Note: We generally do not use the term “deforestation” in order to avoid confusion with technical definitions of this word used by different sectors.</p>

      <p>Datasets such as FORMA alerts, QUICC alerts, MODIS fire alerts, and SAD alerts are “forest cover? loss alerts.”</p>

      <p>Here are key examples of how a few GFW-hosted datasets define these terms.</p>

      <ul>
        <li>The UMD Tree Cover Loss datasets define “tree cover loss” as stand replacement disturbance, or the death of living trees within a 30 m X 30 m area. This definition only applies to areas where canopy cover exceeds 25%, with vegetation over 5 m tall.</li>

        <li>FORMA Alerts indicate areas of 500m X 500m where there is a high probability of tree cover loss. It is important to note that this alert-based system is not the same as an area measurement of tree cover loss.</li>
        <li>QUICC alerts measure significant changes in green vegetation cover.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>For more information on each dataset, please visit our <%= link_to "Data page", sources_path %>.</p>


      <h3>Do GFW data reveal to quality of forest management (e.g. sustainable vs. unsustainable)? What about forest change from natural vs. human causes?</h3>

      <p>GFW forest change data (such as UMD tree cover loss and FORMA alerts) do not necessarily distinguish the quality of the forest management (e.g. sustainable or unsustainable), the legality (illegal or legal), or the cause (e.g. natural or human) of the forest change events. For example, the forest change data available on GFW will include forest change from tree harvesting, fires, pests, and forest clearing for agriculture.</p>

      <p>However, contextual data available on GFW can help users draw more informed conclusions about the nature and drivers of forest change events. For example, users can overlay forest change data over the protected areas layer to flag areas of potential concern. Or users can pull up satellite imagery basemaps to look for “burnscars” “blowdowns”, logging roads, etc.</p>
