      <h3>How was the Global Forest Watch website built?</h3>
      <p>The Global Forest Watch website is an open source platform designed and built by <a href="http://www.vizzuality.com/">Vizzuality</a>, in partnership with the <a href="http://www.wri.org/">World Resources Institute</a>. Data are hosted on <a href="https://cartodb.com/">CartoDB</a>, <a href="https://support.google.com/fusiontables/answer/2571232?hl=en">Google Fusion Tables</a>, and <a href="https://earthengine.google.org/#intro">Google Earth Engine</a>. Map visualizations are powered using CartoDB. The platform is designed for <a href="http://rubyonrails.org/">Ruby on Rails</a> and uses the Global Forest Watch API for data analysis, download, and subscription features. All code is available through our <a href="https://github.com/Vizzuality/gfw">website repository</a> and <a href="https://github.com/wri/gfw-api">API repository</a> on GitHub.</p>

      <h3>What does it mean that Global Forest Watch is in “beta”?</h3>
      <p>While GFW is fully functional, we are still collecting user feedback to improve website features and functionality.</p>

      <p>Establishing an effective web-based tool requires an iterative process of feedback and refinement. This is why your feedback is important to us. Please take our online <a href="https://www.surveymonkey.com/s/gfw2">User Challenge</a> to help us improve the site.</p>
 
      <h3>I am experiencing difficulties with the site. What should I do?</h3>
      <p>Please first ensure that you are using an appropriate web browser. We recommend using a recent version of Google <a href="https://www.google.com/intl/en/chrome/browser/">Chrome</a>, Mozilla <a href="http://www.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/new/">Firefox</a>, or Apple <a href="http://cait2.wri.org/feedback.html">Safari</a>. We highly discourage viewing Global Forest Watch in Internet Explorer due to problems with the map functionality.</p>

      <p>If errors persist when using a recommended browser, please contact us at <a href="mailto:gfw@wri.org">gfw@wri.org</a>.</p>

      <p>GFW is still in “beta”, which means that there may still be some minor issues and errors within the site. We are usually able to fix them in a timely manner. It is helpful if you send us a link to the page or dataset you had open when you encountered the problem, and tell us which browser you are using. If you want to give us general feedback or suggestions about new data or functionality, please use the <a href="http://cait2.wri.org/feedback.html">feedback form</a>.</p>

      <h3>What is the history of Global Forest Watch?</h3>
      <p>The original Global Forest Watch began in 1997 as an initiative to establish a global forest monitoring network around the world, convened by the <a href="http://www.wri.org/">World Resources Institute</a> and partners. The original GFW achieved many outcomes towards the conservation of large intact forest areas. Visit the <%= link_to "About page", about_path %> for the full story.</p>

      <p>Global Forest Watch was re-launched in 2014 with an expanded group of partners and powerful new monitoring capabilities. To learn more about how you can get involved in developing GFW, please take our online <a href="https://www.surveymonkey.com/s/gfw2">User Challenge</a>.</p>
 
      <h3>What features are coming down the road for GFW?</h3>
      <p>Here is a list of additional features that we are working to add to the GFW platform:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>On-the-fly analysis for sub-national administrative areas, concession areas, and protected areas (applicable to all “forest change” datasets)</li>

        <li>Additional “Forest Use” datasets, including concession boundaries for additional countries and commodities.</li>

        <li>Community land claims and tenure rights under the “People” tab</li>

        <li>A “plantation forests map” for the tropical regions</li>

        <li>An updated version of the “Intact Forests Landscapes” layer</li>

        <li>Updated carbon density maps and estimates of emissions for forest loss and land use change</li>

        <li>Mobile optimization for the GFW site</li>

        <li>A citizen-science platform for comparing and classifying satellite imagery of forests. Also an additional crowd-sourcing tool allowing direct upload of geo-referenced information and photos from the field.</li>

        <li>A specialized portal for corporate users </li>

        <li>And much more…</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Who do I contact with questions about the site?</h3>
      <p>Please email general inquiries to <a href="gfw@wri.org">gfw@wri.org</a>.</p>

      <p>For media inquiries, please contact <strong>James Anderson</strong>, <em>Communications Officer, World Resources Institute</em> (<a href="mailto:janderson@wri.org">janderson@wri.org</a>, +1 (202) 729-7608).</p>

      <p>Or, view a <a href="http://www.wri.org/our-work/project/global-forest-watch">list of staff</a> who work on Global Forest Watch. </p>
    </article>

    <article id="corporate">
      <h2 class="corporate source_title">Global Forest Watch for businesses</h2>
      <p>Leading businesses and investors dependent on “forest risk commodities” such as palm oil, soy, beef, and pulp and paper, are recognizing the importance of forests for climate regulation, the provision of ecosystem services, biodiversity protection, and community livelihoods and have made commitments to end deforestation in their supply chains.</p>

      <p>The information generated by Global Forest Watch (GFW) – can support companies as they make business decisions that impact the future of forests.</p>

      <p>GFW is now open for beta testing to users around the world who want to see what is happening in forests in near-real-time. Building off of the core platform, we’re now engaging interested companies to develop a specialized portal geared for corporate users. We envision this platform enabling corporate users to:</p>

      <ul>
        <li>Communicate with customers about deforestation-free commodity production</li>

        <li>Verify that commodity suppliers are in compliance with deforestation-free sourcing policies</li>

        <li>Identify issues as they happen with monthly tree cover loss alerts</li>

        <li>Evaluate compliance with sustainability certification standards</li>

        <li>Assess supply chain risks</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Over the coming year, GFW will develop the corporate portal together with a core group of progressive corporate partners committed to supply chain transparency and ending commodity-driven deforestation. We’ll also establish a working group of interested companies who we’ll invite to test the site as it is developed and provide feedback.</p>

      <p>For more information or to join the conversation, contact: <strong>Elizabeth Baer</strong>, <em>Corporate Engagement Manager for Global Forest Watch</em>, World Resources Institute (<a href="ebaer@wri.org">ebaer@wri.org</a>, +1 (202) 729-7818).</p>

      <p>You can download a copy of GFW’s corporate partnerships policy here <em>(coming soon)</em>.</p>
